  <Instrument_Host>
    <name>The Giotto Spacecraft</name>
    <type>Spacecraft</type>
    <naif_host_id>GIO</naif_host_id>
    <description>The Giotto spacecraft, developed by ESA based on the Geostationary Operational Environment Satellite (GOES) design, inclulded shielding to protect it from dust impacts as it flew by the nucleus of comet 1P/Halley, and subsequently comet 26P/Grigg-Skjellerup. It was a relatively small (2m x 1m, weighing about 960 kg), spin-stabillized spacecraft with three interior platforms on which the experiments were mounted. The 1.5m diamater high-gain dish antenna brought the total spacecraft height to about 3m. The innovative "sandwich" design of the dust shields that protected the spacecraft was based on a design proposed in 1947 by Fred Whipple.</description>
